In 1978, Tiger putted against comedian Bob Hope in a television appearance on The Mike Douglas Show. At age three, he shot a 48 over nine holes at the Navy course. At age five, he appeared in Golf Digest and on ABC's That's Incredible![29] Before turning seven, Tiger won the Under Age 10 section of the Drive, Pitch, and Putt competition, held at the Navy Golf Course in Cypress, California.[30] In 1984 at the age of eight, he won the 9â€“10 boys' event, the youngest age group available, at the Junior World Golf Championships.[31] He first broke 80 at age eight.[32] He went on to win the Junior World Championships six times, including four consecutive wins from 1988 to 1991.[33][34][35][36][37]
